Fatalities, human, dog bite, undiagnosed - Indonesia 980424221520
Date: Fri, 08 May 1998 09:08:01 -0700
From: Dr. James Chin, CDPC-mail
Source: Nando net, May 8, 1998

Indonesian province plans to kill 170,000 dogs to battle rabies
The Indonesian province of East Nusa Tenggara plans to kill more than
170,000 dogs in a campaign to stamp out a rabies epidemic that has claimed
at least eight lives, a report said Friday. The head of the provincial
livestock office T.H. Salean said Thursday an investigation launched by the
health ministry in April confirmed dogs carrying rabies were responsible for
the deaths, the Jakarta Post reported. The mass extermination will be
carried out in East Flores, where local regent Henke Mukin said the disease
would otherwise soon spread to neighboring islands.
"We anticipate that there will be protests from the community, but there is
really no other way. If we don't, more people will die," he was quoted as
saying by Antara news agency. "We understand that people may feel disgusted
about this but which is better: killing the dogs or letting humans die
because of the rabies carried by the dogs," he added. Before the probe,
officials were puzzled by what they called 'mad dog disease' as victims
sometimes survived for as long as a month. Rabies victims normally die one
week after being bitten, Salean said in April. East Nusa Tenggara is 920
miles east of Jakarta and has a population of about 4 million people.
