Date: Wed, 29 Apr 98 9:14:34 -0400
From: David Waltner-Toews <dwaltner-to@ovcnet.uoguelph.ca>

In 1985-87, I worked with the Animal Disease Investigation Centre at
Yogyakarta, Indonesia (one of at least a half dozen such centres in the
country). At that time, both East and West Nusa Tengara were free of rabies,
as well as Bali and the eastern third of the island of Java (East Java).
Nevertheless, the constant movement of small boats among the 13,000 islands
of the Indonesian archipelago certainly makes the entry of rabies into new
territories possible.
In 1986, we investigated an epidemic of rabies in Central Java; rabies is
endemic in West Java, and we were trying to stop its spread into East Java
and hence across into Bali, where the relaxed attitude towards dogs would
make stopping the epidemic very difficult. In the epidemic area, while the
incidence of rabies was higher in stray dogs vs domestic dogs (Relative Risk
= 3), most rabid bites actually came from domestic dogs, which far
outnumbered strays; multiple biting dogs were more often rabid than single
biters. 90% of the rabid dogs died within a week after showing clinical
signs. A few dogs lived longer than 14 days, and at least one dog -
reportedly not showing any clinical signs other than having bitten someone -
was killed after 14 days and was positive for rabies based on histology and
Fluorescent Antibody Test. (see Preventive Veterinary Medicine 1990; 8:295
-303).
--
David Waltner-Toews
Guelph, Canada
e-mail: dwaltner-to@ovcnet.uoguelph.ca
